{
    "id": 5,
    "title": "舆是乎|预制菜or现做菜，要让大家吃个明白",
    "title_zh": "舆是乎|预制菜or现做菜，要让大家吃个明白",
    "source": "学习强国学习平台",
    "link": "https://www.xuexi.cn/lgpage/detail/index.html?id=6045107665007008420&item_id=6045107665007008420",
    "tags": ["预制菜", "食品安全", "产业发展", "消费者权益"],
    "tags_zh": ["预制菜", "食品安全", "产业发展", "消费者权益"],
    "date": "2025-09-16",
    "summary_en": "This article focuses on the discussion of pre-prepared dishes and the issue of their national standards. In 2024, the State Administration for Market Regulation and other departments clearly defined pre-prepared dishes at the national level: they are pre-packaged dishes made from edible agricultural products and their products, processed industrially, and edible only after heating or cooking, with requirements such as 'no preservatives added' and 'promoting clear indication of pre-prepared dishes in catering links'. As a product of food industrialization, pre-prepared dishes are popular for convenience; there are over 70,000 related enterprises in China, the market scale is expected to exceed 600 billion yuan in 2025, and Guangdong's export volume of pre-prepared dishes reached 31.7 billion yuan in 2024. However, the industry still needs improvement; the core of public discussion is not rejecting pre-prepared dishes but demanding 'clear information about what they eat'. The article suggests refining national standards, strengthening supervision, and urging catering enterprises to innovate, focus on consumer needs and operate with honesty. It also notes that both freshly cooked dishes (with 'wok aroma') and standardized pre-prepared dishes have their audiences, and consumers care about food safety, value equivalence and information transparency.",
    "summary_zh": "文章围绕预制菜展开讨论，提及“预制菜国标”问题。2024年市场监管总局等部门从国家层面首次明确预制菜定义：以食用农产品及其制品为原料，经工业化预加工，加热或熟制后方可食用的预包装菜肴，并回应“不添加防腐剂”“推广餐饮环节使用预制菜明示”等公众关切。预制菜因便捷成为餐桌常客，目前我国相关企业超7万家，预计2025年市场规模突破6000亿元，广东2024年预制菜出口额达317亿元。但行业存在待完善之处，公众讨论核心并非抵制预制菜，而是要求“吃个明白”。文章建议国家细化预制菜定义与标注标准、加强监管，餐饮企业需创新、重视消费者需求、坦诚经营。同时指出，“锅气”十足的现做菜与标准化预制菜各受欢迎，消费者在意食品安全、价值对等与信息透明。",
    "best_quote_en": "The core of the discussions around pre-prepared dishes over the years is not that consumers cannot accept them, but that they demand 'clear information about what they eat'.",
    "best_quote_zh": "这几年围绕预制菜的讨论不断，其核心并非消费者不能接受预制菜，而是要求“吃个明白”。"
  }，
{
    "id": 6,
    "title": "I Vibecoded a Dispute Resolution App",
    "title_zh": "我用“氛围编码”开发了一款争议解决应用",
    "source": "LessWrong",
    "link": "https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/6yqt7ywFKux9XbfaG/i-vibecoded-a-dispute-resolution-app",
    "tags": ["Dispute Resolution App", "AI-Assisted Development", "LLM Application", "Web & Mobile Development"],
    "tags_zh": ["争议解决应用", "AI辅助开发", "LLM应用", "网页与移动开发"],
    "date": "2025-09-16",
    "summary_en": "The author developed a dispute resolution app called FairEnough with extensive AI assistance (primarily using Claude Sonnet 4) during free time between consulting projects. The app is designed for scenarios ranging from interpersonal conflicts (like 'r/AmITheAsshole' style) to mild intellectual or professional disagreements. Users can create disputes, invite participants to state their sides, and an LLM generates a 'verdict' (analysis and resolution steps). Participants can accept the verdict or reject it with follow-up details, and rounds repeat until all accept, marking the dispute concluded. The author addresses criticisms: concerns about users abdicating judgment to AI (noting it’s a small hobby project with no commercial plans), AI being prompt-engineered to favor one side (hoping multiple rounds correct this), favoring verbally fluent users (stating this is true in real life too), and data security (storing encrypted data but acknowledging developer access). Additionally, the author shares experiences of learning web/mobile development via LLMs—copying, testing, and understanding AI-generated code (for JavaScript, React, etc.), noting LLMs helped with code structure (substituting 'social onboarding' for coding norms) but had flaws in basic logic. The app has bugs, with a trial link (https://fairenough.netlify.app/) and GitHub repo; beta tester feedback is welcomed.",
    "summary_zh": "作者在咨询项目间隙的空闲时间里，借助大量AI辅助（主要使用Claude Sonnet 4），开发了一款名为FairEnough的争议解决应用。该应用适用于从“Reddit上‘我是不是混蛋’类人际冲突”到较为温和的学术或专业分歧等场景。用户可创建争议、邀请参与者陈述各自立场，LLM会生成“裁决”（包含事件分析及解决步骤）。参与者可接受裁决，或拒绝并补充后续细节，多轮循环直至所有人接受裁决，争议即标记为结束。作者还回应了各类批评：如“让用户放弃自主判断”（强调这是小型爱好项目，无商业化计划）、“AI易被诱导偏袒某一方”（希望多轮机制能修正此问题）、“偏袒语言流利者”（指出现实中亦是如此）、“数据安全”（说明数据加密存储但开发者可访问）。此外，作者分享了通过LLM学习网页/移动开发的经历——复制、测试并理解AI生成的代码（涉及JavaScript、React等），认为LLM在代码结构方面提供了帮助（替代了编程规范的“社交入门”过程），但在基础逻辑上存在缺陷。目前应用仍有部分漏洞，提供试用链接（https://fairenough.netlify.app/）及GitHub仓库，欢迎测试者反馈。",
    "best_quote_en": "FairEnough is a dispute resolution app. It’s intended for anything from ‘r/AmITheAsshole’ types of interpersonal conflicts, to less-heated intellectual or professional disagreements.",
    "best_quote_zh": "FairEnough是一款争议解决应用，适用于从“Reddit上‘我是不是混蛋’这类人际冲突”，到较为温和的学术或专业分歧等各类场景。"
  }，
{
    "id": 7,
    "title": "High-level actions don’t screen off intent",
    "title_zh": "高层级行为无法屏蔽意图",
    "source": "LessWrong",
    "link": "https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/nAMwqFGHCQMhkqD6b/high-level-actions-don-t-screen-off-intent",
    "tags": ["Action and Intent", "Human Behavior", "Moral Psychology"],
    "tags_zh": ["行为与意图", "人类行为", "道德心理学"],
    "date": "2025-09-12",
    "summary_en": "The article challenges the view that 'actions screen off intent'—the idea that the intent behind an action doesn’t matter as long as the action itself is the same (e.g., Alice donating $1k to bed nets is thought to have the same effect regardless of whether she acts out of care or a desire to show off). The author argues this is mostly untrue: human actions contain micro-details (e.g., wording, facial expressions during an apology) filled in by low-level processes, which are shaped by intent and lead to predictable differences in impact, even if the action is perceived as the same (e.g., 'apologizing politely'). Even in distant donations, the recipient organization may discern the donor’s motives and adjust future actions to appeal to similar donors, resulting in different effects based on intent. The author notes the original view can encourage focus on the external world but emphasizes intent’s role in shaping action impact.",
    "summary_zh": "本文反驳了“行为屏蔽意图”的观点——该观点认为只要行为本身相同，背后的意图便无关紧要（例如，爱丽丝捐赠1000美元用于购买蚊帐，无论她是出于对他人的关心还是想向朋友炫耀，人们都认为结果是一样的）。作者提出，这种观点在很大程度上并不成立：人类行为中包含由低层级过程决定的微观细节（如道歉时的措辞、面部表情），这些细节受意图影响，即便行为表面上看似一致（如“礼貌道歉”），也会导致可预见的影响差异。即便在远程捐赠场景中，接受捐赠的机构也可能识别捐赠者的动机，并调整未来行动以吸引类似捐赠者，进而根据不同意图产生不同效果。作者同时指出，“行为屏蔽意图”的观点虽能促使人们关注外部世界，但仍需重视意图对行为影响的塑造作用。",
    "best_quote_en": "One might think 'actions screen off intent': if Alice donates $1k to bed nets, it doesn’t matter if she does it because she cares about people or because she wants to show off to her friends or whyever; the bed nets are provided either way. I think this is in the main not true.",
    "best_quote_zh": "有人可能会认为“行为能屏蔽意图”：如果爱丽丝捐赠1000美元用于购买蚊帐，无论她是出于对他人的关心，还是想向朋友炫耀，或是出于其他任何原因，蚊帐终归会被提供。但我认为，这种观点在很大程度上是错误的。"
  }，
{
    "id": 8,
    "title": "How anticipatory cover-ups go wrong",
    "title_zh": "预期性掩盖如何走向失败",
    "source": "LessWrong",
    "link": "https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/ufj6J8QqyXFFdspid/how-anticipatory-cover-ups-go-wrong",
    "tags": ["Anticipatory Cover-Ups", "Social Dynamics", "Mistrust Spiral", "Rationality"],
    "tags_zh": ["预期性掩盖", "社会动态", "信任螺旋下降", "理性"],
    "date": "2025-08-08",
    "summary_en": "This article explores the problems of 'anticipatory cover-ups'—when one party withholds or covers up information because they anticipate the other party will misuse or misinterpret it. It illustrates the issue through five cases: 1) Official institutions (e.g., CDC, Public Health Scotland) covered up COVID vaccine data for fear of misinterpretation by anti-vaccine groups, which instead reinforced the groups' distrust and led to their misinterpretation of the data. 2) Manager Alice held back feedback on Bob's delayed presentation to avoid upsetting him, making Bob more anxious and his procrastination persist. 3) Small groups (subcultures, religious sects, etc.) covered up internal abuses to protect their reputation, either leading to external distrust when exposed or allowing systemic problems to worsen. 4) The author avoided acknowledging a friend's correct insights for fear the friend would weaponize them, ending the friendship. 5) Wikipedia's policies on 'security through obscurity' (e.g., WP:BEANS) are cited as a related case. The article points out that anticipatory cover-ups often trigger a mistrust spiral, causing more harm (e.g., unaddressed problematic behaviors, inability to evaluate vaccine effectiveness). It quotes Matt Yglesias noting that misinformation mostly confuses one's own side, and concludes there’s no perfect solution, but warns against withholding information due to fears of others’ reactions.",
    "summary_zh": "本文探讨了“预期性掩盖”的问题——即一方因预期另一方会误用或误解某条信息，而选择隐瞒或掩盖该信息。文章通过五个案例展开说明：1）官方机构（如美国疾控中心、苏格兰公共卫生署）因担心反疫苗团体曲解新冠疫苗数据，选择掩盖数据，反而加剧了该团体的不信任，最终导致数据被曲解；2）经理爱丽丝为避免让员工鲍勃不悦，未对其延迟提交演示文稿的行为提出反馈，致使鲍勃焦虑加剧，拖延问题持续存在；3）小团体（亚文化、宗教教派等）为维护声誉掩盖内部虐待行为，要么在曝光后引发外部不信任，要么让系统性问题恶化；4）作者因担心朋友会将正确见解“武器化”，而拒绝承认朋友对自己的正确认知，最终导致友谊破裂；5）引用维基百科的“模糊安全”政策（如WP:BEANS）作为相关案例。文章指出，预期性掩盖往往会引发信任螺旋下降，造成更多危害（如问题行为未得到解决、无法评估疫苗有效性等）。文中还引用马特·伊格莱西亚斯的观点，指出误导信息主要会迷惑己方阵营，并总结称目前虽无完美解决方案，但需警惕因担心他人反应而隐瞒信息的做法。",
    "best_quote_en": "You could call this an anticipatory cover-up: One party anticipates that another will misuse or misinterpret some piece of information. Because of this expectation, they try to withhold or cover up the information.",
    "best_quote_zh": "你可以将其称为预期性掩盖：一方预期另一方会误用或误解某条信息，出于这种预期，他们试图隐瞒或掩盖该信息。"
  }，
